Seems to me that Friedmann is discussing a fairly simple algorithm
for analysing a 1 book cipher; and saying that two messages with
the same (or conformable) start point are needed for that particular
attack. (I don't have the reference easily available, so I am
speculating as to exactly what your authority was saying.)

Consider 3 books XOR'd together (2 key + 1 plaintext, if you will);
the stats are a very long way from flat, and local analysis is
instructive: with a single known plaintext character, digraph
frequencies will reveal a lot about what the adjacent characters
might be in all 3 books.

All I'm saying is that this is not only a weak method; but a method
with uncontrollable weakness. If you have some "book" information,
take (e.g.) the MD5 checksum of each 256 bytes and use it to key
DES for 256 bytes of cipher and you have a lot stronger system.

Robert

